Here's an example of a formula you can use to create a responsive flow chart with hover effects:
1. Create a container div to hold the flow chart:
```
<div class="flow-chart-container"></div>
```
2. Inside the container div, create a series of divs for each step in the process:
```
<div class="flow-chart-step">
  <div class="flow-chart-icon"></div>
  <div class="flow-chart-label">Application submission</div>
  <div class="flow-chart-details">Expected time frame: 1 week<br>Necessary qualifications: Bachelor's degree</div>
</div>
```
3. Add CSS styles to position the step divs and create the hover effect:
```
.flow-chart-container {
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
  justify-content: center;
}
.flow-chart-step {
  position: relative;
  width: 20%;
  margin: 20px;
  cursor: pointer;
}
.flow-chart-icon {
  width: 50px;
  height: 50px;
  background-color: #ccc;
  border-radius: 50%;
  margin: 0 auto;
}
.flow-chart-label {
  text-align: center;
  margin-top: 10px;
}
.flow-chart-details {
  position: absolute;
  top: 100%;
  left: 50%;
  transform: translateX(-50%);
  background-color: #fff;
  box-shadow: 0 0 5px rgba(0,0,0,0.3);
  padding: 10px;
  display: none;
}
.flow-chart-step:hover .flow-chart-details {
  display: block;
}
```
4. Repeat step 2 and 3 for each step in the process.
5. Use media queries to adjust the width of the step divs for different screen sizes:
```
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .flow-chart-step {
    width: 40%;
  }
}
@media (max-width: 480px) {
  .flow-chart-step {
    width: 80%;
  }
}
```
This formula should give you a responsive flow chart with hover effects that displays more detailed information for each step in the process.
